[There have been a total of 3 new cases of WPV1 confirmed since 18 Jun 2014 (see Poliomyelitis - update (11): Brazil ex Eq. Guinea, enviro. samples, global 20140622.2558067 for the 18 Jun 2014 update from the Polio Eradication Initiative website); 2of the 3 cases were in endemic countries (Pakistan and Nigeria), and one was a non-endemic country, Equatorial Guinea. As well described in the update, the polio activity in Equatorial Guinea is related to circulation of a WPV1 similar to that last seen in Cameroon, where vaccination coverages continue to be suboptimal. The hazards of the continued circulation of WPV both in endemic as well as in the non-endemic countries were highlighted earlier this week when information was provided on the isolation of a WPV1, genetically related to WPV1 currently circulating in Equatorial Guinea, in environmental samples in Brazil (see above WHO report and prior ProMED-mail post Poliomyelitis - update (11): Brazil ex Eq. Guinea, enviro. samples, global 20140622.2558067).

Disconcerting are the reports of cVDPV2 cases confirmed in the past week -- 2 in Nigeria and 6 in Pakistan. The presence of cVDPV serves as a further indicator of pockets of susceptibles as the vaccine derived virus would not be circulating in areas with adequate coverages. Where there are cases of cVDPV associated paralytic polio, the risk of WPV associated cases is high if the WPV is introduced. Since January 2014, there have been a total of 25 cVDPV cases (all type 2) confirmed: 16 in Pakistan and 9 in Nigeria (see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Circulatingvaccinederivedpoliovirus.aspx).

Reading the weekly summaries by country can be disturbing for the repetitive statements about vaccination activities being suspended or postponed because of security issues, a sad situation.

For a map showing the locations of all confirmed cases of WPV associated polio in 2014, see the Polio Eradication Initiative map available at: http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Poliocasesworldwide.aspx. - Mod.MPP]
